is throws a `TypeError`. The error is then silently swallowed by `processUser`'s catch block, producing a silent `null` return.\n   - Code context:\n     ```ts\n     // handler.ts:51-54\n     function validate(data) {\n       const name = data.name.trim();\n       return { ok: true, name };\n     }\n     ```\n\n4. Finding 4: Swallowed error in `processUser`\n   - File: `review-src/handler.ts:42-46`\n   - Severity (initial): Important\n   - Description: The catch block in `processUser` returns `null` with no logging and no rethrow. Validation failures — including the null-dereference above — are completely invisible to the caller. The caller receives `null` and has no way to distinguish a validation failure from a legitimate empty result.\n   - Code context:\n     ```ts\n     // handler.ts:42-46\n     try {\n       return validate(payload);\n     } catch (e) {\n       return null;\n     }\n     ```\n\n5. Finding 5: Dead code — `notified` block can never execute\n   - File: `review-src/handler.ts:27-30`\n   - Severity (initial): Suggestion\n   - Description: `notified` is declared `false` and never assigned `true` before the guard `if (notified)`. The `sendAuditLog` call is unreachable on every code path. This is dead code that adds noise and could mislead future editors into thinking audit logging is wired.\n   - Code context:\n     ```ts\n     // handler.ts:27-30\n     let notified = false;\n     if (notified) {\n       sendAuditLog(payload);\n     }\n     ```\n\nBonus (lower priority — include if space permits):\n\n6. Finding 6: Braceless `if` statement (CLAUDE.md violation)\n   - File: `review-src/handler.ts:21`\n   - Severity (initial): Suggestion\n   - Description: `if (payload.admin === true) return processAdmin(payload);` is a single-statement braceless guard. CLAUDE.md states \"Always use braces for control flow bodies: Never write braceless one-liners.\"\n   - Code context:\n     ```ts\n     // handler.ts:21\n     if (payload.admin === true) return processAdmin(payload);\n     ```\n\n7. Finding 7: No-op `sendAuditLog` with TODO\n   - File: `review-src/handler.ts:57-61`\n   - Severity (initial): Suggestion\n   - Description: `sendAuditLog` is a stub with a TODO comment and an empty body. The function has a declared return type `void` and does nothing, yet its call site implies audit logging is wired. The TODO left in a shipped code path is misleading.\n   - Code context:\n     ```ts\n     // handler.ts:57-61\n     function sendAuditLog(payload: RawRequest): void {\n       // TODO: wire the audit sink.\n     }\n     ```\n\n## Project Guidelines\n\nFrom `CLAUDE.md`:\n- \"Always use braces for control flow bodies: Never write braceless one-liners.\"\n- \"Blank lines around control flow and returns.\"\n- TypeScript LSP diagnostics are not authoritative; authoritative signal is the test runner.\n\n## Request\n\nValidate these findings, confirm or reject each, and identify any cross-cutting patterns or additional issues I may have missed.\n","uuid":"d57c5bc2-bc9a-4902-992e-a9c7f7deb48d","session_id":"0bad5584-0a29-4e1a-b600-9947e1c38500"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## Review Scope\n\n`review-src/handler.ts` — a request-handling module that parses a raw HTTP request body, routes to admin or user processing, and optionally logs an audit event.\n\n## Findings\n\n1. Finding 1: Unguarded `JSON.parse` of untrusted input\n   - File: `review-src/handler.ts:17`\n   - Severity (initial): Critical\n   - Description: `JSON.parse(req.body)` runs with no try/catch and no schema validation. A malformed body throws an uncaught `SyntaxError` that propagates up and crashes the handler. Any untrusted caller can send `\"{\"` and the process is unhandled.\n   - Code context:\n     ```ts\n     // handler.ts:15-18\n     export function handleRequest(req) {\n       const payload = JSON.parse(req.body);\n     ```\n\n2. Finding 2: Missing parameter and return types on `handleRequest` and `validate`\n   - File: `review-src/handler.ts:13` and `review-src/handler.ts:51`\n   - Severity (initial): Important\n   - Description: `handleRequest(req)` has no parameter type annotation — `req` is implicit `any`. Likewise `validate(data)` omits a type for `data`. This defeats the type system at the two most critical boundary points (entry and validation). The `processUser` function has the same gap (line 39).\n   - Code context:\n     ```ts\n     // handler.ts:13\n     export function handleRequest(req) {\n     \n     // handler.ts:39\n     function processUser(payload): unknown {\n     \n     // handler.ts:51\n     function validate(data) {\n     ```\n\n3. Finding 3: Null/undefined dereference in `validate`\n   - File: `review-src/handler.ts:52`\n   - Severity (initial): Important\n   - Description: `data.name.trim()` dereferences `data.name` without any guard. If the parsed payload has no `name` field, or it is `null`, this throws a `TypeError`. The error is then silently swallowed by `processUser`'s catch block, producing a silent `null` return.\n   - Code context:\n     ```ts\n     // handler.ts:51-54\n     function validate(data) {\n       const name = data.name.trim();\n       return { ok: true, name };\n     }\n     ```\n\n4. Finding 4: Swallowed error in `processUser`\n   - File: `review-src/handler.ts:42-46`\n   - Severity (initial): Important\n   - Description: The catch block in `processUser` returns `null` with no logging and no rethrow. Validation failures — including the null-dereference above — are completely invisible to the caller. The caller receives `null` and has no way to distinguish a validation failure from a legitimate empty result.\n   - Code context:\n     ```ts\n     // handler.ts:42-46\n     try {\n       return validate(payload);\n     } catch (e) {\n       return null;\n     }\n     ```\n\n5. Finding 5: Dead code — `notified` block can never execute\n   - File: `review-src/handler.ts:27-30`\n   - Severity (initial): Suggestion\n   - Description: `notified` is declared `false` and never assigned `true` before the guard `if (notified)`. The `sendAuditLog` call is unreachable on every code path. This is dead code that adds noise and could mislead future editors into thinking audit logging is wired.\n   - Code context:\n     ```ts\n     // handler.ts:27-30\n     let notified = false;\n     if (notified) {\n       sendAuditLog(payload);\n     }\n     ```\n\nBonus (lower priority — include if space permits):\n\n6. Finding 6: Braceless `if` statement (CLAUDE.md violation)\n   - File: `review-src/handler.ts:21`\n   - Severity (initial): Suggestion\n   - Description: `if (payload.admin === true) return processAdmin(payload);` is a single-statement braceless guard. CLAUDE.md states \"Always use braces for control flow bodies: Never write braceless one-liners.\"\n   - Code context:\n     ```ts\n     // handler.ts:21\n     if (payload.admin === true) return processAdmin(payload);\n     ```\n\n7. Finding 7: No-op `sendAuditLog` with TODO\n   - File: `review-src/handler.ts:57-61`\n   - Severity (initial): Suggestion\n   - Description: `sendAuditLog` is a stub with a TODO comment and an empty body. The function has a declared return type `void` and does nothing, yet its call site implies audit logging is wired. The TODO left in a shipped code path is misleading.\n   - Code context:\n     ```ts\n     // handler.ts:57-61\n     function sendAuditLog(payload: RawRequest): void {\n       // TODO: wire the audit sink.\n     }\n     ```\n\n## Project Guidelines\n\nFrom `CLAUDE.md`:\n- \"Always use braces for control flow bodies: Never write braceless one-liners.\"\n- \"Blank lines around control flow and returns.\"\n- TypeScript LSP diagnostics are not authoritative; authoritative signal is the test runner.\n\n## Request\n\nValidate these findings, confirm or reject each, and identify any cross-cutting patterns or additional issues I may have missed.\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_015PbmsWkGAPGnHTWMNt961j","session_id":"0bad5584-0a29-4e1a-b600-9947e1c38500","uuid":"6f5a3aa1-0442-4472-901b-e54cc64da27d","timestamp":"2026-06-08T06:17:08.036Z","subagent_type":"lz-advisor:reviewer","task_description":"Reviewer consultation for handler.ts"}
